This is `ctx-scan`'s implementation crate root: a standalone tool that walks an arbitrary directory (git or not), maintains a `.context/` sidecar tree of generated summaries, and uses content-hashing (not git) to detect staleness cheaply. Depending on this crate gets you either a CLI binary (`main.rs`) or three programmatic entry points re-exported from `lib.rs` ‚Äî `runner::scan_run`/`check_run`/`update_run` ‚Äî plus `cli::dispatch` for embedding the CLI behavior elsewhere. Everything downstream of `runner.rs` is generic over `ctx_summarize::fs::Fs` and `ctx_summarize::agent::Agent`, so tests exercise real logic against fakes without touching disk or a model.

The staleness pipeline is the crate's central coupling: `walker::walk_dir` produces the scoped file list, `hash::compute`/`load_stored`/`diff` turn that into a `Staleness` (stale dirs deepest-first, changed files, orphan leaves), and `runner::regenerate` consumes it in a fixed order ‚Äî changed leaves, then orphan deletion, then stale-dir rollups ‚Äî because rollups must postdate their children. `runner.rs` only calls `hash::store` and `readme::write_readme` on the "not fresh" path in `update_run`, but always on the `scan_run` path; `check_run` calls neither. Prompt loading is a second cross-cutting quirk: both `runner.rs` and `cli.rs` resolve prompts against the process cwd, never the scanned `base`/`dir`, so any caller that `chdir`s or embeds this crate must be aware prompts don't travel with the target repo.

`cli.rs` and `main.rs` split cleanly: `cli.rs` owns flag parsing, mutual-exclusion enforcement, dispatch logic, and the plaintext output format (`leaves:`/`stale-dir:` etc., a de facto wire contract for scripts); `main.rs` is pure routing ‚Äî agent construction, exit codes, and the stop-hook's always-succeed guarantee. The stop-hook path deliberately never regenerates (deferred to a later `--update`) and always fail-opens, both in `cli::stop_hook`'s design and reinforced by `main.rs` swallowing its result. `walker.rs` and `hash.rs` both depend on `ctx_summarize::cpath`/`fs::scope_matcher` to keep path-mapping and ignore-scope consistent with the sister `ctx-summarize` crate ‚Äî changing scope or sidecar layout in one requires checking the other. `error.rs` is the shared `ScanError` all of the above funnel into via `?`, folding in `SummError` automatically.

Invariant spanning the subtree: a fully fresh tree (per `hash::diff`) results in zero agent calls and zero filesystem writes anywhere in the pipeline ‚Äî `update_run`'s early return is what guarantees this, but it depends on `walker`/`hash` producing correct staleness first.